Target Audience: Executive Assistants & Family Offices

Primary persona: The Executive Assistant


Works for C-suite executives or UHNW individuals

Handles 10-30+ purchasing/sourcing requests per week — everything from office supplies to private jets

Pain: dozens of browser tabs, phone calls to vendors, hours comparing options across price points

Channels: LinkedIn, EA professional networks, concierge service communities, Instagram (personal scrolling)

Decision driver: time savings + reliability ("my boss trusts me to get the best — I need to be sure")


Secondary persona: Family Office Manager


Manages lifestyle logistics for one or more wealthy families

Purchasing ranges from groceries to Gulfstreams — literally anything

Pain: no single tool that covers the full spectrum of what they source

Channels: family office conferences, wealth management networks, LinkedIn, referrals

Decision driver: breadth of coverage + discretion + quality of recommendations


Why this market


Each user represents massive GMV potential (coffee cups to $65M jets)

Revenue via affiliate fees from retailers/vendors — zero friction for the user (free product)

Word-of-mouth is extremely powerful in tight-knit EA/FO networks

Low competition — most AI shopping tools target mass-market bargain hunters, none serve the full price spectrum

Vendor network creates a moat: the more luxury vendors on the platform, the harder to replicate


Go-to-market


Direct outreach to EAs and FO managers via LinkedIn, X, and concierge directories

Position Annie as: "Tell her what you need — anything, any price point — and she handles it"

Zero friction: free to use, no signup approval needed, no budget conversation

Referral loops: one EA tells three others

Tip jar averaging ~20% shows strong user love

Meta Ads targeting EA/FO demographics when ready to scale